05063nam a22007575i 9780812292961DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20162017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979578292  a97808122929617 a10.9783/97808122929612doi  a(DE-B1597)480398  a(OCoLC)965778897  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR5888b.C36 2016eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a821/.72231 aCarlson, Julia S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRomantic Marks and Measures :bWordsworth's Poetry in Fields of Print /cJulia S. Carlson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b31 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Lines on the Lake District: Poetry and the Print Culture of Tourism -- t2. “I Trace His Paths upon the Maps”: Cartographic Inscription in The Prelude -- t3. “Points Have We All of Us Within Our Souls, / Where All Stand Single”: Poetic Autobiography and National Cartography -- tINTERCHAPTER. Native Accents, British Ground: Changing Landscape in the Visual Display of Speech -- t4. Eighteenth-Century Emphasis and Wordsworthian Ontopoetics -- t5. “—You Are Mov’d!”: Lyrical Ballads and the Printing of Local Feeling -- t6. Measuring Distance, Pointing Address: The Textual Geography of the “Poem to Coleridge” and “To W. Wordsworth” -- t7. Thelwall’s Therapoetics: Scanning The Excursion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late eighteenth century, British print culture took a diagrammatic and accentual turn. In graphs of emphasis and tonal inflection, in signs for indicating poetic stress, and in tabulations of punctuation, elocutionists, grammarians, and prosodists deployed new typographic marks and measures to represent English speech on the page. At the same time, cartographers and travel writers published reconfigurations of landscape on large-scale topographical maps, in geometric surveys, and in guidebooks that increasingly featured charts and diagrams. Within these diverse fields of print, blank verse was employed as illustration and index, directing attention to newly discovered features of British speech and space and helping to materialize the vocal and visual contours of the nation.In Romantic Marks and Measures, Julia S. Carlson examines Wordsworth's poetry of "speech" and "nature" as a poetry of print, written and read in the midst of topographic and typographic experimentation and change. Investigating the notebook drafts of "The Discharged Soldier," the printer's copy of Lyrical Ballads, Lake District guidebooks, John Thelwall's scansion of The Excursion, and revisions and editions of The Prelude, she explores Wordsworth's major blank verse poems as sites of intervention—visual and graphic as well as formal and thematic—in cultural contests to represent Britain, on the page, as a shared landscape and language community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aEnglish poetryy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy18th century. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229296140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812292961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers